  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">NENTAD Extension EiE - PLANE</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The conflict in North Eastern Nigeria, which targeted schools and other facilities, has disrupted livelihoods for millions of households, leaving over seven million people in need of humanitarian assistance. More than 2.8 million children need urgent education services. Prior to the crisis, the North East had the highest percentage (52 per cent) of children who never attended schools, with at least 17.1 per cent in Adamawa State and 73 per cent in Yobe State. Moreover, the North East had the highest children drop-out rates, at 3.2 per cent (4.4 for Adamawa and 1.6 for Yobe). The current situation shows a decline in the total number of schools by 22 per cent and a decline in total enrolment by 38 per cent.
As a result of the protracted conflict and mass displacement in remote communities, families and their children are fleeing to urban communities in Borno and Yobe states. The massive displacement has seen more children now accessing education than prior to the crisis, when more than 70 per cent in Borno were out of school. Currently there is a unique opportunity to reach conflict-affected children in Internally Displaced Persons (IDP) camps and host communities with education services. The large class sizes in schools and temporary learning centres demonstrate that there is a huge demand for learning. 

The intervention will be geographically located in;
Borno&amp;#58; Monguno; Gwoza (Pulka), Bama (Bama IDP camp and Banki), Konduga; MMC/Jere LGAs

Yobe&amp;#58; Damaturu, Gujba, and Potiskum LGAs

Specifically, the project will target the following beneficiaries&amp;#58;
&#x2022;	100% of children with disabilities identified during the baseline assessment will receive learning aids based on their individual needs.
&#x2022;	1700 teachers will be trained on TaRL reaching 60,000 children at approximately 35 learners per teacher.
&#x2022;	 96 Government officials (SSO&#x2019;s, QAOs) will improve capacities in training, mentoring, monitoring and data collection of TaRL
&#x2022;	450 teachers will be trained on EGR reaching 18,000 children at approximately 40 learners per teacher
&#x2022;	50 government officials (SSO&#x2019;s, QAO&#x2019;s and head of schools) will improve capacities in training, mentoring, monitoring and data collection of EGR
&#x2022;	1,100 members of SBMCs/CBMCs will be trained on implementation of school emergency preparedness and response plans in 105 schools/IQESs
&#x2022;	4,400 children utilising TLS/renovated classrooms (110 @ approx. 40 learners per TLS/classroom) with WASH facilities 
&#x2022;	2,150 teachers/facilitators will be provided monthly incentives to facilitate teaching at the right level and early grade learning. 
The proposed activities of the extension will support interventions in three output areas&amp;#58; access, quality, and capacity building of systems and local structures to support formal education and Qur&#x2019;anic education. A balanced approach focusing on the immediate education-in-emergencies needs of vulnerable children and the capacity building of government partners to deliver quality education will be deployed as the response moves into early recovery and development. This project supports the achievement of the Global Strategy of learn and lead as it equips the beneficiaries with skills they need to succeed in life and work and have the power to take issues that matter to them.</narrative>
  </description>
